arching reason to write that piece, though, is that Dall-E 2 blew my mind.

What is interesting in retrospect is that the image blow-my-mind moment act=
ually happened before the text blow-my-mind moment, which was the ChatGPT r=
elease in November 2022. That=E2=80=99s the opposite order from how gaming =
and the Internet progressed, but that is because the contraints were differ=
ent: gaming was limited by the ability to display graphics, which came late=
r than the ability to display text, and the Internet was limited by bandwid=
th and standards development.

The constraint with blow-your-mind generative AI, on the other hand, is coh=
erence: does the final product make sense? In this images actually have a b=
ig advantage: first, the amount of data necessary to make a compelling mode=
l has proven to be much less, and second, an image is just a moment in time=
; there are still certain =E2=80=9Crules=E2=80=9D that early image generati=
on struggled with, like hands or text, but even the mistakes could be forgi=
ven as creative license. Text, on the other hand, not only needs to have th=
e proper word order and grammar (the =E2=80=9Crules=E2=80=9D), it also need=
s to have a beginning, middle, and end that is consistent; it was this over=
all coherency that made ChatGPT the second big blow-your-mind moment in gen=
erative AI.

This is all a preamble to say that the third blow-your-mind moment in gener=
ative AI =E2=80=94 this time for video =E2=80=94 has arrived. There are a b=
unch of examples on X demonstrating Veo 2=E2=80=99s capabilities, but I lik=
ed this post that compared the various video generation models=E2=80=99 dep=
iction of slicing a steak:

( https://twitter.com/blizaine/status/1868850653759783033?ref_src=3Dtwsrc%5=
Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1868850653759783033%7Ctwgr%5E8fec24da=
5714e0a6c6e2ca44a35a4b50b412cb8a%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&ref_url=3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Fchrom=
e-headless.local%3A9222%2Fatomic )

What is so impressive is the coherence: Veo 2 is the only model that actual=
ly keeps track of the scene as it progresses. The knife-wielder moves in wa=
ys that makes sense, slices once cut stay where they should be, etc.; every=
 other model is impressive in that they exist and point to what might be po=
ssible, much like Dall-E 1 or GPT-2. Veo 2 actually does it.

The Empire Strikes Back
-----------------------

Veo 2 isn=E2=80=99t the only recent AI announcement from Google:

* Google announced Imagen 3 ( https://blog.google/technology/google-labs/vi=
deo-image-generation-update-december-2024/ ) , the latest version of their =
image generation tool, and probably the best one available ( https://x.com/=
emollick/status/1868715099793338552?s=3D46 ).
* Google announced Whisk ( https://blog.google/technology/google-labs/whisk=
/ ) , a new tool that combines Gemini and Imagen to generate images using o=
ther images as prompts.
* Google expanded the capabilities of NotebookLM ( https://blog.google/tech=
nology/google-labs/notebooklm-new-features-december-2024/ ) , their AI podc=
ast generation tool, to make it interactive.
* Google announced the general availability of Trillium ( https://cloud.goo=
gle.com/blog/products/compute/trillium-tpu-is-ga ) , their sixth-generation=
 TPU.
* Google announced Gemini 2.0 and Gemini 2.0 Flash ( https://cloud.google.c=
om/blog/products/compute/trillium-tpu-is-ga ) , which undergirds everything=
 else.

This post on X referencing OpenAI=E2=80=99s 12 days of announcements captur=
