The reason to focus on Veo 2, however, is not just that it strikes me as a =
seminal moment in generative AI history, but that it also is the most power=
ful manifestation of the advantages that Google has in this space. Think ab=
out the three pillars of generative AI:

* *Algorithms:* Google of course invented the transformer, but it certainly=
 seems likely that the company figured out something important in terms of =
maintaining coherence (which I complained about with Sora ( https://stratec=
hery.com/2024/chatgpt-pro-o1-pro-sora/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsI=
mtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJ=
zdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV0=
0xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L2NoYXRncHQtc=
HJvLW8xLXByby1zb3JhLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNzM3MDM2ODgyLCJpYXQiOjE3MzQ0NDQ4ODIsImlz=
cyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWF=
kIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQgZW50aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3=
ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.TTLGAlbrAffTiaYL=
YbxEXB2C2fktYlAft_NxHyQSFk0bBYVuO7wk6jY7Q6Hx5bl5x4UGGwUrRJdWuLVuuUq2AlbXzHc=
tAsdb1GgQMS2QgHy6JUE14jBemsUjPW0lTguiFRRn3tEyImva2sq17_zNNOfviqf6OlmGoCQpte=
_xKEM-8XwKM30OOx6fZTmKYBdrQ9vjqRRXmypX6uDXWMFg9pQd9aXvC9vJYpah-A3i8nWNjFxOA=
ezBUF_07Y7A8mzV2JUuEiTc4_IrGazK4mDVdDbZV7v08TmYDr5cOmZVcjv1f0VQ0jWRgHiU5anb=
xupLfXt_S8I4pIiXrq2DVaMFdQ ) ).
* *Compute:* Google is training and running inference on its own TPUs =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0which are increasingly developed in conjunction with its models=
 (and Jeff Dean said at NeurIPS that he thinks there are massive more gains=
 to had with further specialization ( https://x.com/jurajselep/status/18684=
58487744733651 ) ).
* *Data:* Data is shaping up to be the biggest obstacle for model developme=
nt going forward; the single-greatest untapped resource is likely video gen=
erally, and YouTube in particular =E2=80=94 which Google owns! I can certai=
nly imagine this was an important resource for the development of Veo 2.

What we saw over the last week was all of these resources being brought to =
bear, and the results are impressive.

Still, the surprise is a matter of perspective: if you told someone in 2020=
 that Google would have a week like this, no one would be surprised; after =
all, Google has been the expected winner in AI for years (which is why Open=
AI was founded in the first place ( https://www.theverge.com/2016/6/2/11837=
566/elon-musk-one-ai-company-that-worries-me ) ). In that light, what was s=
urprising was how surprised Google seemed to be by ChatGPT and the flounder=
ing nature of their initial response; now, though, the company is locked in=
 and starting to show it.

Free ChatGPT Search
-------------------

OpenAI=E2=80=99s 12 days, meanwhile, continued, with an announcement that m=
any observers found relatively underwhelming; from Bloomberg ( https://www.=
bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-12-16/openai-rolls-out-chatgpt-search-feat=
ures-to-all-users ) :

OpenAI is rolling out a search product to all users of its chatbot ChatGPT =
beginning on Monday, escalating its rivalry with Alphabet Inc.=E2=80=99s Go=
ogle. The product, called ChatGPT Search, will be available to any user who=
 is logged in with an account for the chatbot across the company=E2=80=99s =
mobile apps and website, the artificial intelligence startup announced at a=
n event Monday. OpenAI previously made the search option available to paid =
subscribers=E2=80=A6

As part of the expanded rollout, OpenAI users will be able to make the feat=
ure their default search engine via their web browser, the company said. Op=
enAI also demonstrated a new option that will let users ask questions =E2=
=80=94 such as about activities to do in Zurich before Christmas =E2=80=94 =
and have the chatbot respond verbally.

CEO Sam Altman, for one, isn=E2=80=99t impressed by Google:

( https://twitter.com/SamAltsMan/status/1868765115627274289?ref_src=3Dtwsrc=
%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1868765115627274289%7Ctwgr%5E8fec24=
da5714e0a6c6e2ca44a35a4b50b412cb8a%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&ref_url=3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Fchr=
ome-headless.local%3A9222%2Fatomic )

For my part, I will say that I found this announcement more exciting than m=
ost, for the same reasons I was interested in ChatGPT=E2=80=99s new subscri=
ption tier ( https://stratechery.com/2024/chatgpt-pro-o1-pro-sora/?access_t=
oken=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIs=
InR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOi=
JIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZ=
XJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L2NoYXRncHQtcHJvLW8xLXByby1zb3JhLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNzM3MDM2ODgy=
LCJpYXQiOjE3MzQ0NDQ4ODIsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV=
0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5On=
JlYWQgZW50aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6I=
mFjY2VzcyJ9.TTLGAlbrAffTiaYLYbxEXB2C2fktYlAft_NxHyQSFk0bBYVuO7wk6jY7Q6Hx5bl=
5x4UGGwUrRJdWuLVuuUq2AlbXzHctAsdb1GgQMS2QgHy6JUE14jBemsUjPW0lTguiFRRn3tEyIm=
va2sq17_zNNOfviqf6OlmGoCQpte_xKEM-8XwKM30OOx6fZTmKYBdrQ9vjqRRXmypX6uDXWMFg9=
pQd9aXvC9vJYpah-A3i8nWNjFxOAezBUF_07Y7A8mzV2JUuEiTc4_IrGazK4mDVdDbZV7v08TmY=
Dr5cOmZVcjv1f0VQ0jWRgHiU5anbxupLfXt_S8I4pIiXrq2DVaMFdQ ) : I love exploring=
 business model implications! In the case of new subscription tiers, OpenAI=
 is exploring how much it can maximize revenue per user, although as with a=
ll price increases, there is a corresponding reduction in their addressable=
 market; in this case the move to open up search to free users is a clear s=
tep towards an advertising model, which is the largest addressable market p=
ossible.

What makes advertising so compelling and the inevitable end model for consu=
mer tech companies is that you can, over time, continually increase your av=
erage revenue per user without a corresponding reduction in addressable mar=
ket (because it=E2=80=99s still free-to-use). The key to doing that is both=
 having a compelling ad unit and also effective targeting; I suspect the la=
tter is why OpenAI wants users logged in (although I can imagine there are =
rate limit concerns as well, given the relative-to-search marginal costs in=
volved in inference).

Of course Google is the best at monetizing search, but that is precisely wh=
y Altman can have reason to be confident: it is a lot easier to experiment =
and compete when you are building from zero than when you are protecting a =
cash cow; I for one just last week removed the Google app from my home scre=
en in favor of (another) AI chatbot just because I think the experience is =
better (and, of course, search is easily accessible in Safari). Google, of =
course, has a chatbot competitor in Gemini, but Gemini usage is a net negat=
ive for Google, at least to the extent it reduces Google Search usage; Veo =
2 and everything else is immaterial (outside of generative ads, which is a =
huge opportunity). Or, to continue the Star Wars analogy, Google=E2=80=99s =
reliance on traditional search revenue is its exhaust vent, i.e. its bigges=
t potential vulnerability, even as it funds all of the company=E2=80=99s ot=
her advantages.

One additional note on OpenAI, and Sora specifically: I was finally able to=
 make an account, and while the video generation was cool, I was pretty und=
erwhelmed by the quality; it=E2=80=99s hard to imagine ever going to Sora.c=
om once Veo is available.

That leads to an interesting question: why is Sora a separate site with its=
 own account system? Part of it is certainly the extensive user interface t=
hat OpenAI built around the product, which wouldn=E2=80=99t necessarily fit=
 into ChatGPT; another part, however, is almost certainly cost and capacity=
. OpenAI has built up sufficient infrastructure for ChatGPT to support its =
over 300 million weekly active users, but it can=E2=80=99t easily give thos=
e users Sora access with the flip of a switch.

These are good excuses, to be sure, but the reality is that these constrain=
ts =E2=80=94 combined with the underwhelming nature of Sora relative to Veo=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0likely means the product is dead-on-arrival from a business=
 perspective (assuming =E2=80=94 and this is a big assumption =E2=80=94 tha=
t Google makes Veo broadly available in the near future). It=E2=80=99s wors=
e than the competition and doesn=E2=80=99t have any sort of distribution ad=
vantage or the brand awareness of ChatGPT; worse, all of the capacity going=
 towards supporting Sora inference is capacity that can=E2=80=99t go toward=
s ChatGPT and its attempt to disrupt Google. I think that OpenAI would be w=
ell-served in prioritizing ChatGPT going forward.

